AWS EC2 (Elastic Compute Cloud) ‚Äì Notes
1Ô∏è‚É£ EC2

Amazon EC2 provides virtual servers in the cloud called instances.
It allows users to run applications without buying physical hardware.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Instance Types

Instance types define CPU, memory, storage, and networking capacity.
Examples include General Purpose, Compute Optimized, and Memory Optimized.

3Ô∏è‚É£ AMI (Amazon Machine Image)

An AMI is a template used to launch EC2 instances.
It includes the operating system, software, and configuration settings.

4Ô∏è‚É£ Instance Purchasing Options

AWS offers different ways to pay for EC2 instances.
These include On-Demand, Reserved Instances, Savings Plans, Spot Instances, and Dedicated Hosts.

5Ô∏è‚É£ Key Pair

A key pair is used to securely connect to an EC2 instance.
It consists of a public key stored in AWS and a private key downloaded by the user.

6Ô∏è‚É£ Security Group

A security group acts as a virtual firewall for EC2 instances.
It controls inbound and outbound traffic and is stateful.

7Ô∏è‚É£ Elastic IP

An Elastic IP is a static public IP address for EC2.
It allows consistent access even if the instance is stopped or restarted.

8Ô∏è‚É£ Storage (EBS & Instance Store)

EBS provides persistent block storage for EC2 instances.
Instance Store offers temporary storage that is lost when the instance stops.

9Ô∏è‚É£ Auto Scaling

Auto Scaling automatically adds or removes EC2 instances based on demand.
It helps maintain performance and reduces costs.

üîü Load Balancer

A Load Balancer distributes incoming traffic across multiple EC2 instances.
It improves application availability and fault tolerance.
